To add labels to associations in PlantUML, you can use the following syntax:

```
[role1] "label" [role2]
```

Here's an example:

```
@startuml
class Class1 {
  # field1: int
  + method1()
}

class Class2 {
  - field2: String
  + method2()
}

Class1 "1" -- "0..*" Class2 : "has"
@enduml
```

In this example, the label "has" is added to the association between `Class1` and `Class2`.

You can also use cardinality (multiplicity) on both ends of the association by enclosing the values in double quotes:

```
@startuml
class Class1 {
  # field1: int
  + method1()
}

class Class2 {
  - field2: String
  + method2()
}

Class1 "1" -- "0..*" Class2 : "has"
@enduml
```

In this case, the cardinality on the `Class1` side is "1" and the cardinality on the `Class2` side is "0..*".

To add labels to associations in PlantUML, you can use the following syntax:

```
Class1 "label1" -- "label2" Class2 : association_name
```

Here's an example:

```plantuml
@startuml
class Car {
  - make : String
  - model : String
}

class Driver {
  - name : String
  - age : int
}

Car "drives" -- "driven by" Driver : association
enduml
```

In this example, the association between `Car` and `Driver` has the labels "drives" and "driven by" on either side of the association.

You can also use cardinality by enclosing the labels in double quotes:

```plantuml
@startuml
class Car {
  - make : String
  - model : String
}

class Wheel {
  - size : int
}

Car "1" -- "4" Wheel : has
enduml
```

In this example, the cardinality of the association between `Car` and `Wheel` is "1" on the `Car` side and "4" on the `Wheel` side.

Additionally, you can use arrows to indicate the direction of the association:

```plantuml
@startuml
class Car {
  - make : String
  - model : String
}

class Person {
  - name : String
}

Car "1" -- "0..n" Person : owns >
enduml
```

In this example, the arrow `>` indicates that the `Person` class "owns" the `Car` class.

